Title: Core Objects and Functions
Describe: Data classes persist records; service objects and functions coordinate tool execution, state transitions, and loop orchestration.
------------------------------------------------------------
[Example]
S03_CORE_OBJECTS: Data classes and service objects

[Description]
`Task` is the durable `.tasks/task_*.json` record with `id`, `subject`, `description`, `status`, `owner`, `blockedBy`, and optional `worktree`.

`ProtocolState` records shutdown and plan approval requests.

`CronJob` records a cron expression, prompt, recurrence flag, and durability flag.

`MessageBus` sends and reads append-only JSONL mailbox messages.

`MCPClient` is a teaching mock that stores discovered tool definitions and handlers, then calls them through `call_tool`.

[UML]
@startuml
class Task {
  id: str
  subject: str
  description: str
  status: str
  owner: str | None
  blockedBy: list[str]
  worktree: str | None
}
class ProtocolState {
  request_id: str
  type: str
  sender: str
  target: str
  status: str
  payload: str
}
class CronJob {
  id: str
  cron: str
  prompt: str
  recurring: bool
  durable: bool
}
class MessageBus {
  send(from_agent, to_agent, content, msg_type, metadata)
  read_inbox(agent)
}
class MCPClient {
  name: str
  tools: list[dict]
  register(tool_defs, handlers)
  call_tool(tool_name, args)
}
Task -- "JSON file" : asdict/json
ProtocolState -- "pending_requests" : request_id key
CronJob -- ".scheduled_tasks.json" : durable jobs
MessageBus -- ".mailboxes/*.jsonl" : append/read/unlink
MCPClient -- "assemble_tool_pool" : prefixed tools
@enduml

[Detail]
This class diagram answers which objects own state.

`Task`, `ProtocolState`, and `CronJob` are record-like data objects.

`MessageBus` and `MCPClient` are lightweight service objects.

Arrows represent storage or consumption relationships.

`MessageBus.read_inbox` deletes the inbox file after reading, so mailbox reads are destructive.

`MCPClient.call_tool` catches exceptions and returns strings, keeping MCP mock failures inside normal tool-result feedback.

------------------------------------------------------------
[Example]
Key function responsibility table

[Description]
`agent_loop` is the main orchestrator.

`prepare_context` manages context budget.

`call_llm` wraps `with_retry`.

`trigger_hooks` runs permission, logging, large-output, and stop hooks.

`call_tool_handler` normalizes handler invocation and `TypeError` failures.

`spawn_subagent` runs a synchronous subagent; `spawn_teammate_thread` runs an autonomous teammate in a daemon thread.

`start_background_task` moves slow bash-like work into a daemon thread, and `collect_background_results` converts completed work into task notifications.

[UML]
None

[Detail]
Local call responsibilities are easiest to read in three groups:

- Task group: `create_task -> save_task`, `claim_task -> can_start -> load_task`, and `complete_task -> list_tasks/can_start`.
- Context group: `prepare_context -> tool_result_budget/snip_compact/micro_compact/compact_history`.
- Tool execution group: `agent_loop -> trigger_hooks -> should_run_background/call_tool_handler -> trigger_hooks(PostToolUse)`.
